Part 3 - Writing Cold Emails‚úçÔ∏è
‚óè Cold Friendly Offers
‚óã It doesn‚Äôt matter how good your cold email is if you don‚Äôt have what I call a
cold friendly offer.
‚ñ† A cold friendly offer is an offer that is compelling enough to get the
attention of a complete cold stranger while they are mindlessly
scrolling through their email inbox filled with hundreds of other offers.
‚óã Examples of cold friendly offers:
‚ñ† Real Estate Agents: Get 10 Listing Appointments Or You Don‚Äôt Pay
‚ñ† Remodelers: Get 2 New Bathroom Remodels Every Month or You
Don‚Äôt Pay
‚ñ† Mortgage Officers: Get 20 Approved Loan Applications Or You Don‚Äôt
Pay
Roofers: Get 16 New Roofing Replacements Per Month Or You Don‚Äôt Pay
Agency Owners: Get 90 Qualified Sales Calls Per Month Or You Don‚Äôt Pay
You need to understand that with cold email you are sending messages to COLD
STRANGERS, you need an offer that will make you immediately stand out without needing
to say much to get the highest percentage of them on a call with you.
There‚Äôs three steps to creating a cold friendly offer:
‚óè Step 1) Specific Avatar
‚óã You NEED to create an offer for a SPECIFIC person. Just saying that you
help real estate professionals isn‚Äôt specific enough for cold traffic.
‚ñ† You need to choose from Real Estate Agents, Loan Officers,
Wholesalers, or Investors.
‚ñ† However, don‚Äôt get TOO specific or it will backfire. The key is that the
offer resonates with the exact person you are cold emailing.
‚óè Step 2) Specific Outcome
‚óã You NEED to choose the outcome that the market desires the most.
‚ñ† Most people in the real estate niche have slow growth due to
guaranteeing leads or appointments instead of offering the specific
outcome the market desires the most, which is more listing
appointments.
‚ñ† Buyers vs Sellers
‚ñ† Estate AI, Meskula Media, Regain Media all guarantee 10
listing appointments
‚ñ† Another example is remodelers, they specifically prefer bathroom
projects as they are faster to complete and less of a headache than
kitchen projects.
‚ñ† You need to do market research and figure out the exact outcome that
the market desires the most in order for your offer to have the highest
conversions on cold traffic.
‚óè Step 3) Risk Reversal
‚óã You NEED a risk reversal in order for your cold email to get the highest
number of meetings.
‚óã Most people fail to understand that a risk reversal or guarantee is used at the
marketing level but not the sales level.
‚ñ† By the time most prospects get on the call they won‚Äôt even mention
the guarantee or risk reversal but without it they would have never
responded to your cold email and
‚óè certainly would have never agreed to get on the call in the first place.
‚óè A risk reversal can be:
‚óã A Money Back Guarantee (Highest Converting)
‚ñ† This only works with conditions
‚óã Or We Work For Free
‚ñ† This is good, but in the cold email you want to still use the word
‚ÄúGuaranteed‚Äù
‚óã 30 Day Satisfaction Guarantee
‚ñ† If by the end of the first 30 days the client doesn‚Äôt feel like you‚Äôre the
team to get them to the specific outcome, they get a refund.
‚óè A money back guarantee is always gonna be the highest converting risk reversal as
being able to say ‚ÄúOr You Don‚Äôt Pay‚Äù helps you immediately stand out.
‚óã What most of the top guys do is create a money back guarantee to use at the
marketing level but on the backend it has conditions in order for the prospect
to even apply for it.
‚óã For example these conditions may include:
‚ñ† $20-50/day minimum ad spend
‚ñ† Contact All Leads in 48 Hours
‚ñ† Respond To Our Team in 72 Hours
‚ñ† Consume All Required Training Content
‚ñ† Update CRM every 48 hours
‚ñ† Etc.
‚óã The idea is that you choose conditions that make it unreasonable that the
prospect doesn‚Äôt achieve the desired outcome.
‚óè This allows you to use the extremely powerful guarantee in your cold email without
taking on much extra risk on your end.
‚óè The truth is some prospects won‚Äôt even be able to apply for the guarantee but they
would have never got on the sales call without it.
‚óã This may sound unethical to some people but it‚Äôs what all the top guys are
doing so if you want to compete at that level I‚Äôd recommend doing the same.
‚óã I‚Äôve never seen a prospect get mad about this, again most of them will forget
about the guarantee by the time they get
‚óè on the call but in the worst case scenario you just downsell them on a different
guarantee.
‚óè Again, the guarantee is used at the marketing level in your cold email to 5-10x the
amount of meetings you book, but then you should rely on your sales process to
convert them on the call.
‚óã If they ask about the guarantee on the call just say something along the lines
of ‚ÄúYeah, so we guarantee the 10 listing appointments as long as you invest
the minimum ad spend and do all of the work on your end.‚Äù
Subject Lines
‚óè After you‚Äôve created your cold friendly offer you can start writing your cold emails.
‚óè The first step is your subject lines.
‚óã The main goal of the subject line is to pique the prospect‚Äôs curiosity and get
them to open the email.
‚óã However, remember this is cold email and not email marketing so don‚Äôt do
anything salesy or how you would market to your email list.
‚óã I try to mimic internal emails that are sent within the organization or company
when creating subject lines.
‚ñ† The less formal, the better.
‚ñ† Avoid using capitalization
‚óã A good rule of thumb is to start with the subject line ‚Äúquick question‚Äù and use
the open rate as a baseline to test other subject lines down the road.
‚óã You can also test using personalized variables in your subject lines.
‚ñ† Examples of top performing subject lines:
‚ñ† quick question
‚ñ† {{firstName}} - quick question
‚ñ† {{firstName}}, thoughts?
‚ñ† question for {{firstName}}
‚ñ† question about {{companyName}}
‚ñ† {{firstName}}?
‚ñ† Again, don‚Äôt overthink this step, just start with ‚Äúquick question‚Äù to get a
baseline open rate that you can test against later down the road.
‚ñ† If the leads are from Outscraper then use ‚Äúquestion about
{{companyName}}‚Äù or quick question
Anatomy of A Cold Email
‚óè I typically write 3-4 line cold emails that are relevant, fit on an iPhone screen (70% of
emails are opened on mobile), and straight to the point.
‚óè These emails are broken into the sections shown below:
1. The Opener
‚óè The Body
‚óè (optional) A Case Study
‚óè The Call To Action
‚óè Signature
‚óè I will break down how to write all 5 sections and then how to put them all together.
Writing The Opener
‚óè Cold email openers are the first sentence in the cold email and also act as a second
subject line.
‚óè A good opener should convey to the prospect that the email was written just for them,
even if it really wasn‚Äôt.
‚óè Try to make it as relevant as possible to the prospect who‚Äôs going to be reading it as
relevance is the key to good cold emails.
‚óã Top Performing Cold Email Openers:
‚ñ† I came across you while searching for realtors in Miami.
‚ñ† As a real estate agent in Miami, I imagine you‚Äôre always looking for
ways to generate more seller opportunities.
We want to show them in as little words as possible, exactly why they should respond to our
cold email.
The best body will always be presenting your cold friendly offer and positioning it in a way
that makes the prospect want to learn more about how it works, eliciting a response.
‚óè Again, having a risk reversal will 10x your results.
Make sure your offer is easily quantifiable, a specific result in a specific time frame.
Understand your current market‚Äôs level of sophistication and awareness, if needed you may
need to position your mechanism as unique and avoid overused keywords.
‚óè If your market is constantly hearing ‚ÄòFacebook Ads‚Äô, avoid using keywords related to
Facebook ads and create your own unique mechanism.
‚óã You can learn more about this by reading about Eugene Schwartz‚Äôs levels of
market sophistication.
‚óã For example, instead of saying ‚ÄúOur Facebook Ads will bring you 10 listing
appointments or you don‚Äôt pay‚Äù, you can say:
‚ñ† We have a way to bring you 10 listing appointments using our seller
attraction system - or you don‚Äôt pay!
‚ñ† We have a way to bring you 10 listing appointments through our
Youtube Ads system - or you don‚Äôt pay!
I‚Äôve found that using specific numbers can make your offer seem more realistic and easier to
comprehend to the prospect.
‚óè For example, we had a campaign where we said ‚Äú7 listing appointments‚Äù instead of
10.
‚óè Or another campaign where we said ‚Äú52 in-home appointments‚Äù instead of 50.
‚óã This comes from the book ‚ÄúScientific Advertising,‚Äù using specific numbers
makes the claim more believable and easier to comprehend.
‚óã Most people use common numbers to describe their offer like 5, 10, 20, etc.
‚óã Being oddly specific adds a level of realism to the claim, like it‚Äôs from a
specific real-life example or case study, even if it‚Äôs not.
Simplicity is the ultimate form of sophistication‚Ä¶
‚óè Top Performing Body Examples
‚óã We can get 57 paid trials to come into your gym for a workout next month
using our end-to-end lead nurturing process - or you don‚Äôt pay.
‚ñ† Was searching for the top auto detailers in Northridge and came
across Endless Summer Detailing - congrats on the 5 star rating!
‚ñ† Was searching for the top lawn care companies in Boston and came
across TrueGreen‚Äôs website - you guys have some great reviews!
‚ñ† Was searching for gyms here in San Diego and came across Planet
Fitness.
‚ñ† Noticed you play a major role in Remodeling Pro‚Äôs marketing efforts - I
imagine you‚Äôre always looking for ways to maximize the budget.
‚ñ† As a fellow agency owner, I imagine you‚Äôre always looking for more
ways to fill up your calendar with more sales calls.
‚ñ† As the founder of a SaaS company, I imagine you‚Äôre always looking
for ways to hire experienced SDRs.
‚ñ† Was searching for top solar companies in Kingman and came across
SolLife - keep up the great work!
‚ñ† Was scrolling through Facebook and came across one of
{{companyName}}‚Äôs ads.
Writing The Body
‚óè After the prospect reads the opener we want to give them context on exactly what we
can do for THEM.
‚óè We help agents like yourself get an extra 7 listing appointments every 5 months
guaranteed.
‚óè We have a way to bring you 16 solar installs over the next 30 days - or you don‚Äôt pay.
‚óè We can help you sell 20 more used cars each month using our car dealership
accelerator system - or you don‚Äôt pay.
‚óè We can book 15 meetings on your sales rep‚Äôs calendar each month - and you only
pay per booked meeting that shows.
‚óè We have a way to bring you 10 listing appointments over the next 6 months,
guaranteed.
‚óè We can bring you 2 bathroom remodeling projects over the next 30 days - or you
don‚Äôt pay.
Writing The CTA
‚óè The CTA is the last line of the cold email and should give the prospect a clear next
step as to what they have to do to learn more about the offer you presented in the
body.
‚óè The best CTAs are often soft and conversational, avoiding sounding corporate or
overly professional.
‚óè Always make sure the CTA is a question that can easily be answered and is
‚Äúlow-risk‚Äù to the prospect.
‚óã For example, if you‚Äôre asking the prospect to meet on a 45-minute Zoom call,
that is ‚Äúhigh-risk‚Äù for the prospect.
2. That‚Äôs 45-minutes of time they may never get back and a Zoom call is
a bigger commitment than a phone call.
3. So a ‚Äúlower-risk‚Äù CTA would be asking for permission to send more
info or to have a quick 5-min chat.
‚óè Don‚Äôt make the prospect feel pressured to book a call, even with a cold friendly offer,
you‚Äôre still a complete stranger who emailed them.
‚óè Always make sure that the CTA flows with the opener and the body, I‚Äôd recommend
reading it aloud to yourself.
‚óã Send the email to your inbox and open it, put yourself in the prospect's shoes,
does the email make sense?
‚óè One of my favorite CTAs is just ‚ÄúMind if I send more info?‚Äù because it‚Äôs extremely
low-risk and gets a high throughput of interested leads.
‚óè Using a soft CTA will allow you to test the cold email angle/offer faster and get better
results if you‚Äôre in a saturated market.
‚óè It‚Äôs important to understand there‚Äôs three types of CTAs:
2. Hard CTA - goes straight for the meeting
3. Soft CTA - asks for permission to send more info
‚óè Value CTA - asks for permission to share something of value such as a video or sales
asset
‚óè Hard CTA Examples:
‚óã Are you interested in learning more?
‚óã Are you open to learning more?
‚óã Do you have 12 minutes for a call this week?
‚óã Are you open to a quick call to discuss this further?
‚óã Would it make sense if we meet sometime this week to talk this through?
‚óã Any interest in connecting on a call to learn more?
‚óã Any interest in hearing how the system works?
‚óã Open to discussing how we can do the same for you?
‚óã Open to exploring this further?
‚óã How does Monday suit you for a quick chat?
‚óã Is this worth exploring for {{companyName}}?
‚óè Soft CTA Examples:
‚óã Mind if I send more info?
‚óã Mind if I share more info about how this works?
‚óã Do you mind if I send more information on this?
‚óã Would you like more info before we put something on the calendar?
‚óè Value CTA Examples:
‚óã Would you like to see a quick video explaining further?
‚óã Mind if I send a quick video explaining the system?
‚óã Mind if I send a quick Loom on this?
‚óã Mind if I send a quick video explaining how we can implement this for
{{companyName}}?
‚óã I made a Google Doc on how we implement this, cool if I share it?
‚óã I made a resource on this, mind if I share it with you?
Adding A Signature
‚óè Without a signature it‚Äôs hard for the prospect to trust you based on a random cold
email.
‚óè Having an optimized signature shows that you‚Äôre a real person and that they could
Google you and your company if they wanted.
‚óè Adding a phone number to your signature will also occasionally result in interested
leads who skip responding to the cold email and call you.
‚óè You can also add a link to your calendar in the signature for interested prospects who
don‚Äôt wanna waste time going back and forth over email.
‚óè If you have a small following on YouTube, LinkedIn, or Instagram you can link it in
your signature to increase your credibility and authority.
‚óè Adding a business address/phone number also tells Google and the prospect that
you are likely a real person and not a scammer.
‚óã Signature Framework
‚ñ† [Full Name]
‚ñ† [Role] | [Company Name]
‚ñ† [Let's Chat]
‚ñ† [Phone Number]
‚ñ† [City & Zip Code]
‚ñ† [Youtube or LinkedIn]
‚óã Example:
‚ñ† Jackson Williams
Founder | Lead Odyssey
Let‚Äôs Chat
(818) 566-8712
Northridge, 91324
Let‚Äôs Connect On LinkedIn!Adding Case Studies
‚óè Adding case studies to your cold email is an easy way to separate yourself from the
competition and increase the booking rate.
‚óã If you have them, I 100% recommend using them in some part of your cold
email sequence.
‚óè You can either put the case study as the body, after the body, in the P.S. section, or
use it in one of your follow-ups.
‚óè There‚Äôs really no best place to put it, as long as you include it.
‚óè Make sure to use a relevant case study that flows with the rest of the cold email.
‚óã It shouldn't be from a different avatar than the cold email is targeting.
‚óè Make sure the case study is tangible and includes a specific end result, something
that the prospect can easily visualize and understand.
‚óã Case Study Example #1 - The Body
‚ñ† In this example, you essentially just use a relevant case study as the
body of the cold email.
‚ñ† Hey {{firstName}},
I came across you while searching for realtors in Miami.
