Experimentation
‚óè The simple cold email framework I just taught you works, it‚Äôs easy to follow, and will
get meetings coming in the door.
‚óã However, don‚Äôt be afraid to branch out and try your own things after you get
the ball rolling.
‚ñ† As long as your cold emails have a no-brainer offer and are short,
concise, relevant, and straight to the point, you can test different ways
of writing them.
‚ñ† Also, try and keep every email below 280 characters or 50 words and
remember the majority of readers will be on Mobile.
‚ñ† And never talk about yourself more than you talk about the prospect.
‚ñ† Keep a 2:1 ratio, you should be speaking about the prospect
2x as much as you speak about yourself.
‚óè As long as you follow these basic rules I would strongly recommend experimenting
and trying new angles and ways of formatting your cold emails.
‚óè For example, the following 1-sentence cold email added six figures of MRR for one of
our clients.
‚óã Apologies if this is too upfront, but we have a way to bring you more work for
your home improvement company.
Mind if I send more?
Kind Regards,
{{signature}}
‚óè It‚Äôs different from the framework above, but it follows most of the basic rules.
Sales Assets
‚óè If you‚Äôre in an extremely saturated niche you can also try just offering a sales asset or
video in your cold email using a value-based CTA.
‚óã Most of the people I know in the ecommerce niche offer some type of sales
asset in order to make cold email work in such a saturated niche.
‚óã Then when a prospect responds you just send them the sales asset and
include a CTA in the response when you send it to them.
‚ñ† You can also include an option to book a call inside of the actual sales
asset.
‚óã This allows you to stand out in the prospect‚Äôs inbox, get a higher throughput
of positive responses, and provide value upfront.
‚óã A sales asset can be a case study, SOP, or process documented inside of a
Google Doc or Gamma Project that will be of extreme value to your ICP.
‚óã It can also be a free training or case study breakdown video hosted on a
landing page with a book a call button.
‚óè Examples of using a sales asset in your cold email:
‚óã Hey {{firstName}} - we just helped ABCMarketing book 17 qualified sales calls
in the first 30 days of working with us and I documented the entire process we
used from A-Z.
Mind if I send it over so you can use the same process at {{companyName}}?
‚óè Hey {{firstName}},
Just came across {{companyName}}‚Äôs ad on Facebook - wanted to reach out.
Recently we partnered with GymShark to 2x their email marketing revenue in 37
days by adding our plug-n-play flows.
Mind if I send over the flows so you can do the same at {{companyName}}?
‚óè Hey {{firstName}},
I just put together a list of 2,000 leads that could be your ideal client.
Mind if I send it over?
Follow Up Sequences
‚óè After writing your initial cold email, the next step is to write your follow-up sequence.
‚óã The beautiful thing about cold email automation is that we can also automate
a follow-up sequence of additional emails for when the prospect doesn‚Äôt
respond to the initial cold email.
‚óã The best follow-up sequences flow together and remain relevant to the first
cold email (for the most part).
‚ñ† I typically send each lead a total of 5 emails until they respond, so the
initial cold email plus 4 additional follow-ups.
‚ñ† This allows you to get the most squeeze out of the lemon.
‚ñ† Keep in mind that an alternative strategy is to only send 2
emails per every lead, get better deliverability, and focus on
VOLUME/contacting more leads per month.
‚ñ† This can work if you have a very large TAM.
‚óè Always split test each of your follow-ups the same way you would test multiple cold
emails.
‚óè If you have a case study and haven‚Äôt used it in your cold email yet, a great place to
put it is in your follow-ups.
‚óè It‚Äôs okay to use Call-To-Actions in some of your follow-ups.
‚óè If you have sales assets, you can offer to send them in your later follow-ups.
‚óã This may catch the attention of new prospects who have been ignoring your
sequence up until that point.
‚óè Never send a break-up email that willingly cuts off communication with a prospect.
‚óã Instead, you can send what's called a ‚ÄúPass Off Email‚Äù and ask them if there‚Äôs
anyone else at the company you should reach out to.
‚óè My secret weapon is having a 5th email sent at least 17 days from the 4th email and
framing it as a new email.
‚óã A big part of cold emailing is timing, so if they ignore your first 4 emails, it‚Äôs
best to wait over two weeks before sending the 5th and final email in the
sequence.
